 beyond contextualization to lead the reader through a fundamental rethinking of how we understand and interpret the classic tradition.A luminous work of scholarship by one of today’s leading classicists, Helen of Troy in Hollywood highlights the importance of ancient myths not as timeless stories frozen in the past but as lenses through which to view our own artistic, cultural, and political moment in a new light. This incisive book demonstrates how, whether as the hero of these screen adaptations or as a peripheral character in male-dominated adventures, the mythic Helen has become symbolic of the perceived dangers of superhuman beauty and transgressive erotic agency.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMythology, Greek, in motion pictures. 0aMythology, Greek, on television. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aAchilles and Patroclus.  aActing.  aAdvertising.  aAlien invasion.  aAmber Heard.  aAmerican Girl.  aAmerican Pop.  aAncient Greece.  aAncient Greek art.  aAnimation.  aAnita Loos.  aAva Gardner.  aBette Davis.  aBrad Pitt.  aBreen (Star Trek).  aBride.  aBritney Spears.  aCinema of the United States.  aClose-up.  aClothing.  aClytemnestra.  aConcubinage.  aCosmetics.  aCostume designer.  aCostume.  aCourtship.  aDemetrius and the Gladiators.  aElaan of Troyius.  aElopement (marriage).  aEpisode.  aEuripides.  aExoticism.  aFan magazine.  aFashion.  aFeature film.  aFemininity.  aFeminism.  aFemme fatale.  aFlapper.  aFrat House.  aGender bender.  aGrace Kelly.  aGrace Lee (director).  aGreek alphabet.  aGreek mythology.  aGreta Garbo.  aHelen O'Loy.  aHelen of Troy.  aHer Story (video game).  aHollywood Romance.  aHollywood Star.  aJean Harlow.  aJennifer Aniston.  aJoan Cra